atus=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|8 October 1921\n[[SS Mount Clay]]\n\n[[Hamburg]][[File:SS Mount Clay Exterior.JPG|center|thumb]]<br />\n|18 October 1921\nNew York\n|Sevcik - Marie (1898-1943),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:J6L7-Z6J|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Sevcik|date=1921|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1922\n|Masek - Emilie (1904-2000)\n\nEmilie was the younger sister of Frantisek and Josefa.\n|[[File:Emily Ma\u0161kov\u00e1-Kutzendorfer (1904-2000).png|center|thumb|133x133px|Emily Ma\u0161kov\u00e1-Kutzendorfer (1904-2000)]]\n|-\n|28 September 1922\n[[RMS Saxonia (1899)|RMS Saxonia]]\n\nCherbourg[[File:RMS Saxonia (1899).jpg|center|thumb]]<br />\n|9 October 1922\nNew York\n|Vitek - Jan (1907-1941)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JNVW-L4C|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Vitek|date=1922|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|\n|possibly after 1922\n|Sevcik - Josef (1906-1961)\n|\n|-\n|\n|before 1960\n|Moravec - Antonie (1881-1960)\n|\n|}\n\n== Culture ==\nHistorically, social life commonly took place in pubs where men drank, narrated, and cheered with many staying until morning, coming home to \"hear the endless lamentation of his wife.\" Mysl\u00edv's grandmothers regularly went to church for rorates in the morning, and in the evening they drove feathers around the cottages. The washing of the feathers was then closed by doders, when they were singing, feasting and dancing. In the carnival time, villagers disguised in masquerade would run around, representing a traditional shaggy laufra, a masked figure walking at the head of the procession, a running Jew with a punch on his back, a photographer or a mare.\n\nGod's punishment for wasting food and goods was widely believed and money would be spent carefully so as to not be condemned for scandalism. People in the village and in the city counted every issued tailor. So, for example, the bark for tannery was peeled from the trees that had been slaughtered during the sap, and the peeled peeling consisted of borders for paper mills. The woodcutters used the brush and the skins at home by cutting them into small pieces and tied them in haggles. These were then settled on the walls throughout the summer. Wads, dry lands and stumps have served as (today one would say excellent ecological) fuel throughout the winter.\n\n== Notable Residents ==\nPetr Vodi\u010dka (1856 - 1911) - teacher\n\nHe was a native of Ro\u017emit\u00e1l pod T\u0159em\u0161\u00ednem, where his father was a miller. He attended a primary school. Later his family moved to Prague, where he attended the main school in Sm\u00edchov and later the grammar school in Mal\u00e1 Strana, then moved to the industrial school in Sm\u00edchov and finally to a real German school in the Old Town of Prague. He then completed his education at the ck Czech Institute for Teacher Education in Prague. In 1877 he was appointed interim administrator of the school in Lu\u017eenice near Doma\u017elice. At the beginning of the school year 1879 he was appointed a definitive teacher at a three-class school in Kolinec. Three years later, he was appointed head teacher in Myslov, where he spent the rest of his life. He died of a stroke visiting his brother in P\u00edsek in 1911.\n\n[[:cs:Ladislav Stehl\u00edk|Ladislav Stehl\u00edk (1908 - 1987)]] - poet, writer\n\nHe was born on 26 June 1908 in house number 36 in [[B\u011bl\u010dice]], lying between [[Blatn\u00e1]] and B\u0159eznice. It is a landscape full of ponds, forests, meadows and intact natural corners inviting for thought. He spent his childhood in this region. His whole life is permeated with the memory of this early period, which is primarily associated with boy's fun, pasture work and the entire cycle of village life. It was during his childhood that he began to fully perceive the beauty of nature, the awareness of home, and to foster an understanding of the poor, rural people.\n\nIn his native town of B\u011bl\u010dice Ladislav Stehl\u00edk attended elementary school, then attended a secondary school in Blatn\u00e1. He spent his childhood joyfully and happily in B\u011bl\u010dice. He did not grow up in a wealthy family, so he and his siblings helped his parents to the farm. Most of all, he liked work on pasture. It was not just work for him, but also fun. As a cowherd boy, he tasted the smell of potato-baked potatoes, kid's games and other pleasures that rural life provided him with in the unspoilt nature.\n\nIn 1924 -1928 he studied at the Teaching Institute in P\u0159\u00edbram. Here he met many of his friends. After graduation, Ladislav began working as a teacher. He first taught at elementary schools around his birthplace, in Leletice, Hud\u010dice and Koupi. From May 1930 until the liberation in 1945, ie for fifteen years, he worked as a teacher in the village of \u0160umava at the elementary school in Mysl\u00edv, Klatovy.\n\nLadislav Stehl\u00edk's Mysl\u00edv stay inspired him to write six poetry collections. This secluded rural environment did not isolate him from cultural events: he contributed to various magazines, collaborated on editing the P\u0159\u00edbram Proceedings Dr\u00faza and constantly maintained friendly and social relations with many important artistic personalities of South and South-Western Bohemia, Podbrdy, Pilsen and Prague. Most, however, gravitated to Pilsen. This became the center of regional poets during Stehl\u00edk's stay in Thinking. Here he often met with his artistic friends and discussed with them cultural events and art.\n\nHis friends, whom he had among the simple rural people and the artists, then visited him at home in Myslov. These included Josef and Karel \u010capek, Jan \u010carek, Franti\u0161ek Halas, Josef Hora, Franti\u0161ek Ka\u0161par, V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nezval, Jaroslav Seifert and Karel Vok\u00e1\u010d, as well as translators Pavel Eisner, V\u00e1clav Pol\u00edvka, Vlastimil Rada, Vojt\u011bch Sedl\u00e1\u010dek, V\u00e1clav \u0160p\u00e1la.\n\nIn 1945, Ladislav Stehl\u00edk and his family moved to Prague, an apartment in Vinohrady, which was left to him by Franti\u0161ek Halas. He refused the offered positions at the Ministry of Information and the Ministry of Education modestly and continued to pursue his teaching profession. He taught gradually at three Sm\u00edchov schools until 1966, when he retired and continued to pursue literary work.\n\nIn 1968, on the anniversary of his 60th birthday, he was awarded the title of Merited Artist. He died on September 11, 1987 in Prague and at his request was buried in his native B\u011bl\u010dice. The grave of Ladislav Stehl\u00edk is decorated with a bust by sculptor B\u0159etislav Benda.\n\nBlanka Stehl\u00edkov\u00e1 (1933) - historian\n\nArt historian, journalist PhDr. Blanka Stehl\u00edkov\u00e1 Csc. Was born on 26 August 1933 in B\u0159ezov\u00e9 Hory. After the school in Myslivna she attended the Federal Girls' Gymnasium in Ceske Budejovice and from 1945 until 1951 the State Real Grammar School of Jan Masaryk in Prague. Then she graduated from the Faculty of Arts, Charles University in Prague, majoring in the history of art. She was awarded the diploma of the candidate of sciences, for her dissertation Czech Engaged Graphics 1917 - 1927, in 1989. She is rich in her professional activities in the field of 20th century art (especially graphics and book illustrations). and documentation of the Union of Czechoslovakia. also as an editor of Evening Prague. From 1986 to 1991 she was a member of the jury of the Most Beautiful Book of Czechoslovakia. Since 1990 she has been a member of the Scientific Council of the Terez\u00edn Memorial. Her curatorial and publishing activities are also rich. She is also the author of numerous newspaper and magazine articles. In 1986 she was awarded the prize of the Union of Czech Artists for two contributions in the field of book and illustration, two commemorative medals of the Terez\u00edn Memorial and in 2007 she received the V\u00e1clav Hollar Medal.\n\nFranti\u0161ek Wawre\u010dka (1920) - soldier\n\nMr. Franti\u0161ek Wawre\u010dka was born on 3 April 1920 in Ostrava - Z\u00e1b\u0159eh as the third of five children. He spent his childhood in Z\u00e1b\u0159eh, and for many years he moved to V\u00edtkovice with his parents. He trained as a modeller and worked in V\u00edtkovice Ironworks.\n\nIn the summer of 1939, the war was coming and Mr. Franti\u0161ek Wawre\u010dka and his friend decided to go to Poland, where the military group of General Ludv\u00edk Svoboda was formed. Their journey led through Poland to the Soviet Union through Moscow and Odessa, the ship sailed through the Bosphorus and Dardanelles and through Istanbul further to the Middle East to Palestine to General Klap\u00e1lek. As members of the Infantry Battalion, they were sent by the Western Desert to occupied Tobruk Fortress in Libya. Here he spent almost three years of war hardship with various movements along the Mediterranean coast.\n\nIn 1942 they were retrained to an anti-aircraft regiment and temporarily anchored in Palestinian Haifa as an airport defense. In 1943 they circumnavigated the African continent to England, where Mr. Wawre\u010dka took a course for drivers and became a member of the motorized battalion. In 1944 they besieged French Dunkirk and remained there until the end of the war. Mr. Wawre\u010dka returned to his native country - Czechoslovakia after a long six-year period.\n\nHe also met his future wife Helena Sporkov\u00e1 in Mysl\u00edva, whom he married in the autumn of 1945. They went to Ostrava for a short time, where their son Vladim\u00edr was born. Since Mrs. Helena Wawre\u010dkov\u00e1's father was left alone in Myself, everyone returned. From 1947, Mr. Wawre\u010dka began working in Plze\u0148sk\u00e1 \u0160koda as a wood-modeler with whom he was trained. He remained faithful to this job until 1970, when he retired.\n\nFor his courage and bravery, which Mr. Wawre\u010dka showed by going abroad, he received many awards and honors such as Czechoslovak War Cross, Polish War Cross, Medal of Valor, Medal for Defense of Poland, African Star of the Eighth Brigade, Award 1939-45, Star for Participation in war, Medal of Merit, for the fight against fascism, commemorative medals and many others. At the end of 2005, Mr. Wawre\u010dka was awarded the highest French Order of the Legion of Honor and was appointed Knight of the Legion of Honor. In 2006 he was solemnly named Honorary Citizen of Mysl\u00edv Municipality.\n\nStanislav Kub\u00edk (1930) - researcher\n\nProfessor, ing. Stanislav Kub\u00edk, doctor of technical sciences, full member of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences, was born November 15, 1930 in the family blacksmith village Mysl\u00edva. He attended elementary school in Mysl\u00edva, the Secondary School in Nepomuk and the Industrial School in Pilsen. He obtained his engineering degree at the University of Mechanical and Electrical Engineering (V\u0160SE) in Pilsen, then he completed his scientific studies at the Faculty of Electrical Engineering of the Czech Technical University in Prague. He is one of the founders of the field of technical cybernetics in Czechoslovakia and the main builder of this field at V\u0160SE in Pilsen. He worked as the head of the Department of Technical Cybernetics and was the Rector of the University of Economics in Pilsen. After leaving the University of Economics, he was the director of the Institute of Information Theory and Automation of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences (\u010cSAV), the scientific secretary of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences and then the vice-chairman of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences.\n\nHe achieved the most important professional results in the field of analysis and synthesis of nonlinear dynamic systems. He is the author and co-author of many scientific and professional articles and treatises published in Czech and foreign journals and conferences, twelve monographs published in Czechoslovakia and abroad, and research reports resulting from cooperation with industrial and research organizations.\n\nMarta's wife is an electrical engineer. The younger daughter died tragically in 1972. The older daughter is an engineer, the granddaughter is a doctor, the grandson is studying at the University of Economics in Prague.\n\n== Landmarks ==\n\n* Church of the Assumption\n* Rectory\n\n== Districts ==\n\n* '''Mysl\u00edv'''\n* Lou\u017en\u00e1\n* Mil\u010dice\n* Nov\u00fd Dv\u016fr\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Mysl\u00edv (021).jpg|Village square\nFile:Mysl\u00edv, d\u016fm IV.jpg|Houses\nFile:Mysl\u00edv, pam\u011btn\u00ed deska.jpg\nFile:Mysl\u00edv (004).jpg\nFile:Mysl\u00edv (017).jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{commons category|Mysl\u00edv}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080618131004/http://www.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0322/ Czech Statistical Office: Municipalities of Klatovy District]\n\n{{Klatovy District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mysliv}}\n[[Category:Villages in Klatovy District]]\n", "name_user": "Jonnychiwa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysl%C3%ADv"}
{"title_page": "Burari", "text_new": "{{unsourced|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Burari\n| native_name                     = Murari\n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = \n| settlement_type                 = city\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| nickname                        = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Delhi\n| pushpin_label_position          = [[File:Burari-hospital.jpg|thumb|This image represent Burari Government hospital which made by Delhi Government]]\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|28.755|N|77.199|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Delhi]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Central Delhi]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = [[BJP]]\n| current minister                = Manoj Tiwari ([[Bhartiya Janta party]])\n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = 146,190\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 110084\n| registration_plate              = \n| demographics1_info1             = [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[English language|English]]\n| Literacy Rate (Avg. %)          = 93.98%\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Burari''' is a [[constituency]] in [[Central Delhi]] District in the [[National Capital Territory of Delhi]], India. There is a ''[[Mahabharata]]'' era [[temple]] called Khandeswar Mandir dedicated to [[Shiva]]. It is the place where [[Arjuna]] prayed to [[Shiva]] before burning the Khandav Prastha (later known as Indraprastha) Van. According to folklore, [[Krishna]] came here to graze cows. It was named ''Murari'', which during the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal period]] changed into ''Burari''.\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of the 2011 India census, the population of Burari in 2011 is 146,190.\n\nNearby areas are [[Bhalswa Jahangir Pur|Bhalswa]], [[Jahangirpuri metro station|Jahanghirpuri]], [[Rohini, Delhi|Rohini]], Nirankari colony, [[Mukherjee Nagar]], Jagatpur, [[Kingsway Camp]], GTB Nagar, [[Wazirabad, Delhi|Wazirabad]], and the north campus of [[University of Delhi|Delhi University]].\n\n== Government ==\nPresently, the following are the government representatives from respective parties in Burari.\n\n* [[Manoj Tiwari]], Member of Parliament, [[Bharatiya_Janata_Party|BJP]], 2019 - present.\n* [[Sanjeev Jha]], MLA ([[Member_of_the_Legislative_Assembly_(India)|Member of Legislative Assembly]]), [[Aam_Aadmi_Party|Aam Aadmi Party]], 2015 - 2020, Won again in the 2020 elections from Burari, with the highest margin of 88,000 votes.\n* Anil Kumar Tyagi, Counselor, BJP, 2017-present, North Delhi Municipal Corporation.\n\n== Transport Services ==\nGovernment's [[Delhi Transport Corporation|DTC]] buses, [[Delhi Integrated Multi-Modal Transit System|DIMTS]] Cluster buses, feeder buses of [[Delhi_Metro_Rail_Corporation|DMRC]], private minibusses, 3-wheelers, and 4 wheelers ''Gramin Sewa'' vehicles ( also known as ''Phat-Phat Sewa,'' common for short distances) are common modes of transport. Mobile App based [[Uber]] and [[Ola Cabs]] services are also available.\n\nFollowing are the route numbers of DTC/Cluster buses which gives services to Burari or parts of Burari (only a few bus stands are mentioned to give an idea of the route of buses including start and end point bus stands ) :\n* '''143''' (''Keshav Nagar (Mukti Ashram Nathupura) - GTB Nagar - [[Kashmiri Gate, Delhi|Kashmiri Gate]] ([[Kashmiri Gate ISBT|ISBT]]) - Anand Vihar ISBT ([[Swami_Vivekanand_Inter_State_Bus_Terminus|Viveka Nand ISBT]])'')\n* '''162''' (''Tiggi Pur- Burari - GTK Depot'')\n* '''185''' (''Nathu Pura -[[GTB Nagar metro station|GTB Nagar]] - [[Kashmiri Gate, Delhi|Kashmiri Gate]] ([[Kashmiri Gate Inter State Bus Terminal|ISBT]]) - [[Red Fort]] - [[Central Secretariat metro station|Central Secretariat]]'')\n* '''185''' '''STL''' (Nathu Pura - Nirankari Colony - BBM II Depot )\n* '''192''' (''Keshav Nagar (Mukti Ashram Nathupura)- Kashmiri Gate (ISBT)'')\n* '''192''' '''STL''' (''Keshav Nagar (Mukti Ashram Nathupura)- GTB Nagar'')\n* '''912''' (''Burari - GTB Nagar - Maurice Nagar -[[Punjabi_Bagh|Punjabi Bagh]] Terminal -Vishnu Garden NW Chowk'')\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in North Delhi district]]\n\n\n{{Delhi-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unsourced|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Burari\n| native_name                     = Murari\n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = \n| settlement_type   