egory:Haile Selassie]]\n[[Category:Abrahamic religions]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Haile Selassie]]\n[[Category:World Christianity]]\n", "name_user": "Midnightblueowl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMansions of Rastafari:correcting citation location.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rastafari"}
{"title_page": "Foster/White Gallery", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American commercial art gallery}}\nThe '''Foster/White Gallery''' is an art gallery in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], in the United States. It was started as the '''Richard White Gallery''' in 1968 in the [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] neighborhood.\n\n== History ==\n\nRichard White started the Richard White Gallery at 311\u00bd Occidental Street, in the [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] district of Seattle, in 1968. In 1973, he sold it to Donald Foster, who renamed it the Foster/White Gallery.<ref name=obit>{{cite web |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/obituaries/obituary-longtime-seattle-gallery-owner-don-foster-nurtured-fine-art-in-region/ |title=Obituary: Longtime Seattle gallery owner Don Foster nurtured fine art in region |newspaper=Seattletimes.com |date=April 7, 2012 |first=Gayle |last=Clemans |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Donald Foster Historylink\">{{cite web |url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=9618 |title=Foster, Donald Isle (1925-2012) |newspaper=Historylink.org |date=April 4, 2012  |first=Peter |last=Blecha |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> Foster sold it in December 2002 to the Huang family, owners of the [[Bau-Xi Gallery]] in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"seattletimes.nwsource.com\">{{cite web |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20021205&slug=foster05 |title=Foster/White Gallery sold |newspaper=Community.seattletimes.nwsource.com |date=December 5, 2002 |first=Sheila |last=Farr |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=biz>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2002/12/02/daily50.html |title=Canadian art gallery owners buy Seattle's Foster/White |newspaper=[[Puget Sound Business Journal]] |date=December 5, 2002 |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> In April 2006 it moved to a renovated building at 220 3rd Avenue South, a few blocks from its original location.<ref name=\"SADA map\">{{cite web |url=http://www.seattleartdealers.com/map.html |title=Seattle Art Dealers Association Members' Map |newspaper=Seattleartdealers.com |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> It earlier had other premises in Kirkland, Rainier Square, and Pioneer Square.<ref name=biz/>\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Foster/White was one of five galleries which started the ''Pioneer Square Exhibition Magazine'', a monthly magazine to publicise their shows.<ref name=mag>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130207191251/https://www.seattleartdealers.com/guide.html |title=SADA Exhibition Guide |newspaper=Seattleartdealers.com }} Archived February 7, 2013.</ref> In 1990 the gallery was among the founding members of the Seattle Art Dealers Association,<ref name=sada>{{cite web |url=http://www.seattleartdealers.com/ |title=Seattle Art Dealers Association |newspaper=Seattleartdealers.com |date=  |author= |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> which in 2005 took over publication of the magazine, renaming it the ''SADA Exhibition Guide''.<ref name=mag/>\n\nThe gallery shows mostly [[contemporary art]] and work by artists of the [[Northwest School (art)|Northwest School]].{{cn}} Some work by [[Kenneth Callahan]], [[Alden Mason (artist)|Alden Mason]], [[Mark Tobey]] and [[George Tsutakawa]] is permanently on show.<ref name=fodor>{{cite web |url=http://www.fodors.com/world/north-america/usa/washington/seattle/things-to-do/sights/reviews/fosterwhite-gallery-429700 |title=Foster/White Gallery Review |newspaper=Fodors.com |date=  |author= |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> The first Seattle showing of glass work by [[Dale Chihuly]] was at the gallery in 1977.<ref name=obit /> [[Janna Watson]] showed work there in 2016.<ref name=st>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/visual-arts/five-must-see-art-shows-for-august/ |title=Five must-see Seattle art shows in August |newspaper=Seattle Times |date=  |author= |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|47|36|01|N|122|19|48|W|format=dms|display=title|type:landmark_region:US-WA}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.fosterwhite.com}}\n\n{{Northwest School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foster White Gallery}}\n[[Category:1968 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Art galleries established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Art galleries in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Museums in Seattle]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American commercial art gallery}}\nThe '''Foster/White Gallery''' is an art gallery in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], in the United States. It was started as the '''Richard White Gallery''' in 1968 in the [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] neighborhood.\n\n== History ==\n\nRichard White started the Richard White Gallery at 311\u00bd Occidental Street, in the [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] district of Seattle, in 1968. In 1973, he sold it to Donald Foster, who renamed it the Foster/White Gallery.<ref name=\"Seattle Times Richard White obituary\">{{cite web |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/obituaries/obituary-longtime-seattle-gallery-owner-don-foster-nurtured-fine-art-in-region/ |title=Obituary: Longtime Seattle gallery owner Don Foster nurtured fine art in region |newspaper=Seattletimes.com |date=2012-04-07 |first=Gayle |last=Clemans |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Donald Foster Historylink\">{{cite web |url=http://www.historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=9618 |title=Foster, Donald Isle (1925-2012) |newspaper=Historylink.org |date=2012-04-04  |first=Peter |last=Blecha |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> Foster sold it in December 2002 to the Huang family, owners of the [[Bau-Xi Gallery]] in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"seattletimes.nwsource.com\">{{cite web |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20021205&slug=foster05 |title=Foster/White Gallery sold |newspaper=Community.seattletimes.nwsource.com |date=2002-12-05 |first=Sheila |last=Farr |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Bizjournals.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2002/12/02/daily50.html |title=Canadian art gallery owners buy Seattle's Foster/White |newspaper=[[Puget Sound Business Journal]] |date=2002-12-05 |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> In April 2006 it moved to a renovated building at 220 3rd Avenue South, a few blocks from its original location.<ref name=\"SADA map\">{{cite web |url=http://www.seattleartdealers.com/map.html |title=Seattle Art Dealers Association Members' Map |newspaper=Seattleartdealers.com |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> It earlier had other premises in Kirkland, Rainier Square, and Pioneer Square.<ref name=\"Bizjournals.com\"/>\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Foster/White was one of five galleries which started the ''Pioneer Square Exhibition Magazine'', a monthly magazine to publicise their shows.<ref name=\"Pioneer Square Exhibition Magazine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.seattleartdealers.com/guide.html |title=SADA Exhibition Guide |newspaper=Seattleartdealers.com |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> In 1990 the gallery was among the founding members of the Seattle Art Dealers Association,<ref name=\"SADA main page\">{{cite web |url=http://www.seattleartdealers.com/ |title=Seattle Art Dealers Association |newspaper=Seattleartdealers.com |date=  |author= |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> which in 2005 took over publication of the magazine, renaming it the ''SADA Exhibition Guide''.<ref name=\"Pioneer Square Exhibition Magazine\"/>\n\nThe gallery shows mostly [[contemporary art]] and work by artists of the [[Northwest School (art)|Northwest School]].{{cn}} Some work by [[Kenneth Callahan]], [[Alden Mason (artist)|Alden Mason]], [[Mark Tobey]] and [[George Tsutakawa]] is permanently on show.<ref name=\"Fodors.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fodors.com/world/north-america/usa/washington/seattle/things-to-do/sights/reviews/fosterwhite-gallery-429700 |title=Foster/White Gallery Review |newspaper=Fodors.com |date=  |author= |accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> The first Seattle showing of glass work by [[Dale Chihuly]] was at the gallery in 1977.<ref name=\"Seattle Times Richard White obituary\" /> [[Janna Watson]] showed work there in 2016.<ref name=\"Seattle Times\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/visual-arts/five-must-see-art-shows-for-august/ |title=Five must-see Seattle art shows in August |newspaper=Seattle Times |date=  |author= |accessdate=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|47|36|01|N|122|19|48|W|format=dms|display=title|type:landmark_region:US-WA}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.fosterwhite.com}}\n\n{{Northwest School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foster White Gallery}}\n[[Category:1968 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Art galleries established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Art galleries in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Museums in Seattle]]\n", "name_user": "Justlettersandnumbers", "label": "safe", "comment": "archive 1 ref, human-readable dates etc", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foster/White_Gallery"}
